Retail Vendor Insights Report (Python,SQL and Tableau)

  • Tech Stack: Python, ETL Pandas Tableau SQL
  • Github URL: Retail Vendor Project Repo
  • Dashboard URL: Dashboard

Business Problem

Effective inventory and sales management are critical for optimizing profitability in the retail and wholesale industry.

The goal of this analysis is to identify underperforming brands, determine top vendors contributing to sales and gross profit,

assess cost benefits of bulk purchasing, analyze inventory turnover, and compare profitability across vendor tiers.

Exploratory Data Analysis Insights — Summary Statistics

  • Negative & Zero Values:
  • Gross Profit has a minimum of approximately -52,002.78, indicating potential losses due to high costs or heavy discounts.
  • Profit Margin shows extreme negatives when revenue is zero or less than total cost.
  • Some products have zero sales, pointing to slow‑moving or obsolete stock. Outliers Detected by High Standard Deviations:
  • Purchase & Actual Prices show very high maxima relative to means (e.g., ~5,681.81 & 7,499.99 vs ~24.39 & 35.64).
  • Freight Cost varies widely (≈0.09 to ≈257,032.07), suggesting potential logistics inefficiencies.
  • Stock Turnover ranges from 0 to ~274.5; values >1 can reflect sales fulfilled from older stock.

Data Filtering

  • To focus on reliable, profit‑relevant insights, the analysis excluded rows where:
  • Gross Profit ≤ 0
  • Profit Margin ≤ 0
  • Total Sales Quantity = 0

Correlation Insights

Purchase Price vs Total Sales Dollars & Gross Profit: Weak (around −0.012 and −0.016).

  • Total Purchase Quantity vs Total Sales Quantity: Strong (~0.999), indicating tight inventory alignment.
  • Profit Margin vs Total Sales Price: Negative (~−0.179), possible margin pressure at higher prices.
  • Stock Turnover vs Gross Profit & Profit Margin: Weak negative (≈ −0.038 & −0.055).

Research Questions & Key Findings

1) Brands for Promotional or Pricing Adjustments

  • 198 brands exhibit lower sales but higher margins—candidates for targeted marketing and price optimization. 2) Top Vendors by Sales & Purchase Contribution
  • Top 10 vendors contribute ~65.69% of total purchases; remaining vendors ~34.31% (risk of vendor concentration). 3) Impact of Bulk Purchasing on Cost Savings
  • Large orders receive ~72% lower unit cost (e.g., ~$10.78 per unit vs. higher costs in smaller orders). 4) Vendors with Low Inventory Turnover
  • Approximate unsold inventory capital: ~$2.71M, implying cash‑flow and storage inefficiencies. 5) Profit Margin: High vs Low‑Performing Vendors
  • Top Vendors' Profit Margin (95% CI): (~30.74%, ~31.61%), Mean ~31.17%.
  • Low Vendors' Profit Margin (95% CI): (~40.48%, ~42.62%), Mean ~41.55%.
  • Interpretation: Low‑performing vendors hold higher margins but weaker volumes. 6) Statistical Validation
  • A two‑sample test rejects the null of equal margins between top and low‑performing vendors.

Final Recommendations

Re‑price low‑sales, high‑margin brands to stimulate volume without eroding profitability.

  • Diversify vendor partnerships to reduce concentration risk.
  • Leverage bulk purchasing to maintain competitive unit economics.
  • Address slow‑moving inventory via purchase planning, targeted promotions, and clearance.
  • For top vendors: fine‑tune price/cost levers and consider bundles to lift profit.
  • For low vendors: invest in distribution, marketing, and calibrated price moves to grow volume.
